Right so figure 1 from Renshaw et al. is broken into a series of plots

Ren1

Panel a) is time versus DNA copy number, but only for Temperature == -20 and Preservation == CTAB

ggplot(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==-20,],aes(x=factor(Duration),y=CopyNumber))+
  geom_boxplot()

We can see how they calculated the stats using the standard anova function in R

anova(lm(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==-20,],CopyNumber~factor(Duration)))

Fix the x and y axis and add some text to the plot

ggplot(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==-20,],aes(x=factor(Duration),y=CopyNumber))+
  theme_bw()+
  stat_boxplot(geom='errorbar', linetype=1, width=0.5)+
  geom_boxplot()+
  xlab("")+
  ylab(bquote('DNA copy number (copies/4 ' ~mu~ 'L)'*''))+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("0" = "Fresh", "1" = "1 week","2" = "2 weeks"))+
  annotate("text", x = 1, y = 1800, label = "a")+
  annotate("text", x = 2, y = 2600, label = "b")+
  annotate("text", x = 3, y = 2600, label = "b")+
  annotate("text", x = 1, y = 5000, label = "ANOVA: p < 0.01")

Panel b) is similar (just change the x groupings) here Temperature == 20 and Preservation == CTAB

ggplot(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==20,],aes(x=factor(Duration),y=CopyNumber))+
  geom_boxplot()

Statistics as performed in Renshaw et al. are fairly simple using ANOVA (a specific type of linear regression where the explanatory variables are factors)

anova(lm(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==20,],CopyNumber~factor(Duration)))

You can combine multiple ggplot figures into a single plot using grid extra

First create an object for each figure

p1<-ggplot(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==-20,],aes(x=factor(Duration),y=CopyNumber))+
  theme_bw()+
  stat_boxplot(geom='errorbar', linetype=1, width=0.5)+
  geom_boxplot()+
  xlab("")+
  ylab(bquote('DNA copy number (copies/4 ' ~mu~ 'L)'*''))+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("0" = "Fresh", "1" = "1 week","2" = "2 weeks"))+
  annotate("text", x = 1, y = 1800, label = "a")+
  annotate("text", x = 2, y = 2600, label = "b")+
  annotate("text", x = 3, y = 2600, label = "b")+
  annotate("text", x = 1.3, y = 5000, label = "ANOVA: p < 0.01")+
  annotate("text", x = 0.6, y = 1000, label = "(a)")
  
p2<-ggplot(data=Ren1[Ren1$PreservationBuffer=="CTAB"&Ren1$Temperature==20,],aes(x=factor(Duration),y=CopyNumber))+
  theme_bw()+
  stat_boxplot(geom='errorbar', linetype=1, width=0.5)+
  geom_boxplot()+
  xlab("")+
  ylab(bquote('DNA copy number (copies/4 ' ~mu~ 'L)'*''))+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("0" = "Fresh", "1" = "1 week","2" = "2 weeks"))+
  annotate("text", x = 1, y = 1800, label = "a")+
  annotate("text", x = 2, y = 4500, label = "b")+
  annotate("text", x = 3, y = 4500, label = "b")+
  annotate("text", x = 1.3, y = 5000, label = "ANOVA: p < 0.01")+
  annotate("text", x = 0.6, y = 1000, label = "(b)")

Then combine them using grid

grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=1)

#save using png(), pdf() ect

png(filename="FileName.png",width=960,height=480,res=150)
grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=1)
dev.off()
